  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered a violation of the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is universally recognized as a violation of the law. Here's a concise breakdown:\n\n1. **Definition**: Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained funds to make them appear legitimate. It typically follows crimes like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption.\n\n2. **Legality**: \n   - **United States**: Criminalized under the Bank Secrecy Act (1970) and the Money Laundering Control Act (1986), with penalties including imprisonment and fines.\n   - **United Kingdom**: Prohibited by the Proceeds of Crime Act (2002).\n   - **European Union**: Governed by Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD), enforced by member states.\n   - **Global Standards**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets international guidelines, pressuring countries to adopt anti-laundering laws.\n\n3. **Process Criminalized**: Each stage\u2014placement (introducing illicit funds into the financial system), layering (obscuring the trail), and integration (reintroducing \"clean\" money)\u2014is illegal.\n\n4. **Professional Accountability**: Banks, lawyers, and accountants must comply with \"Know Your Customer\" (KYC) and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations to prevent inadvertent complicity.\n\n5. **Global Consensus**: While enforcement varies, nearly all jurisdictions criminalize money laundering to avoid international sanctions or blacklisting. Offshore havens face increasing pressure to comply.\n\n6. **Penalties**: Severe consequences include asset forfeiture, imprisonment, and fines. International cooperation (e.g., intelligence sharing, asset freezing) strengthens enforcement.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious criminal offense worldwide, with robust legal frameworks and international efforts to combat it.",
